  <chapter xml:id="ch-vector-spaces">
    <title>General Vector Spaces</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        In earlier chapters we developed core ideas of linear algebra inside the concrete
        setting of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.  This chapter abstracts those ideas to
        <em>general vector spaces</em>, where the “vectors” need not be geometric arrows
        nor columns of numbers—often they are polynomials, matrices, functions, or
        sequences.  We’ll see that the familiar notions of linear combination, span,
        independence, subspace, basis, and dimension all extend seamlessly to this broader
        setting and often make diverse applications look the same “up to structure.”
      </p>
      <objectives>
        <ul>
          <li>Recognize and use the vector space axioms to verify a structure is a vector space.</li>
          <li>Work fluently with span and linear independence in abstract spaces.</li>
          <li>Identify and test subspaces; compare spans of different generating sets.</li>
          <li>Construct bases and compute dimensions in both finite‑ and infinite‑dimensional examples.</li>
        </ul>
      </objectives>
    </introduction>

