    <!-- =========================================================
         2. VECTOR SPACE AXIOMS
    ========================================================== -->
    <section xml:id="vs-axioms">
      <title>Vector Space Axioms</title>

      <p>
        We now formulate the common structure you observed above.  Throughout, let
        <m>K</m> be a field (e.g., <m>\mathbb{R}</m> or <m>\mathbb{C}</m>).
      </p>

      <definition xml:id="def-vector-space">
        <title>Vector space over a field</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A <em>vector space</em> over <m>K</m> consists of a set <m>V</m> together with
            operations of addition <m>V\times V\to V</m>, <m>(u,v)\mapsto u+v</m>, and
            scalar multiplication <m>K\times V\to V</m>, <m>(k,u)\mapsto ku</m>, such that
            for all <m>u,v,w\in V</m> and <m>k,\ell\in K</m>, the following hold:
          </p>
          <ol label="(A1)">
            <li><em>Commutativity:</em> <m>u+v=v+u</m>.</li>
            <li><em>Associativity:</em> <m>(u+v)+w=u+(v+w)</m>.</li>
            <li><em>Additive identity:</em> there is <m>0\in V</m> with <m>u+0=u</m>.</li>
            <li><em>Additive inverse:</em> each <m>u</m> has <m>-u</m> with <m>u+(-u)=0</m>.</li>
            <li><em>Distributivity (vectors):</em> <m>k(u+v)=ku+kv</m>.</li>
            <li><em>Distributivity (scalars):</em> <m>(k+\ell)u=ku+\ell u</m>.</li>
            <li><em>Associativity (scalars):</em> <m>k(\ell u)=(k\ell)u</m>.</li>
            <li><em>Multiplicative identity:</em> <m>1u=u</m>.</li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <remark>
        <p>
          The scalars need not be real numbers; any field works.  We often say “<m>K</m>‑vector space”
          to emphasize the underlying field.  Many examples below (polynomials, matrices,
          functions, sequences) satisfy all axioms with standard operations.  See the Activities
          for non‑standard operations that <em>break</em> an axiom and thus are not vector spaces.
        </p>
      </remark>

      <subsection xml:id="vs-examples">
        <title>Examples (and a non‑example)</title>

        <example xml:id="ex-Rn">
          <title><m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> and <m>K^n</m></title>
          <p>
            With component‑wise addition and scalar multiplication, <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> (and more generally
            <m>K^n</m>) is a vector space.  All axioms follow from ordinary arithmetic in <m>K</m>. 
          </p>
        </example>
        <example xml:id="ex-P2">
          <title>Quadratic polynomials</title>
          <p>
            <m>P_2=\{ax^2+bx+c: a,b,c\in K\}</m> with usual polynomial addition and scalar multiplication
            is a vector space.  Axioms are verified coefficientwise. 
          </p>
        </example>

        <example xml:id="ex-Mmn">
          <title>Matrices</title>
          <p>
            <m>M_{m,n}(K)</m> with entrywise addition and scalar multiplication forms a vector space.
          </p>
        </example>

        <example xml:id="ex-functions">
          <title>Function spaces</title>
          <p>
            For any nonempty set <m>X</m>, the set <m>\mathrm{Func}_{X,K}</m> of functions <m>f:X\to K</m>,
            with pointwise addition and scalar multiplication, is a vector space. 
          </p>
        </example>

        <example xml:id="ex-sequences">
          <title>Infinite sequences</title>
          <p>
            The set of sequences <m>(a_i)_{i\in\mathbb{N}}</m> with termwise addition and scalar
            multiplication is a vector space; we denote it <m>\mathrm{Seq}_K</m>. 
          </p>
        </example>

        <example xml:id="ex-nonexample">
          <title>A non‑example via broken addition</title>
          <p>
            Let <m>V=M_{2,3}(\mathbb{R})</m> but define a “sum” by <m>A\oplus B=A</m> (ignore the second addend),
            keeping usual scalar multiplication.  Then commutativity fails (<m>A\oplus B\neq B\oplus A</m> in general),
            so this is <em>not</em> a vector space. 
          </p>
        </example>
      </subsection>



     <subsection xml:id="vs-consequences">
        <title>Consequences of the axioms</title>
        <proposition xml:id="prop-elementary-consequences">
          <title>Elementary consequences</title>
          <statement>
            <ol>
              <li>The additive identity is unique; if <m>u+v=u</m> then <m>v=0</m>.</li>
              <li>Additive inverses are unique; if <m>u+v=0</m> then <m>v=-u</m>.</li>
              <li><m>0u=0</m> for all <m>u\in V</m>.</li>
              <li>(Cancellation) If <m>u+w=v+w</m> then <m>u=v</m>.</li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
        </proposition>
        <p>
          These follow directly from the axioms by short algebraic manipulations. Assign your group to prove (1)–(3);
          then use (1)–(3) to establish (4). 
        </p>
      </subsection>

      <activities>
        <activity xml:id="act-vs-axioms-check">
          <title>Activity: Axioms in action</title>
          <p>
            On <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> define <m>(a,b)\oplus(c,d)=(a+d,b+c)</m> with usual scalar multiplication.
            Decide which axiom fails (if any).  Repeat with
            <m>(a,b)\oplus(c,d)=(0,b+d)</m> and with <m>c\odot(a,b)=(a,cb)</m>, keeping the still‑usual operation
            unchanged each time.  Justify each conclusion precisely. 
          </p>
        </activity>
      </activities>
    </section>


    <section xml:id="vs-span-indep">
      <title>Linear Combinations, Span, and Linear Independence</title>

      <definition xml:id="def-linear-combination">
        <title>Linear combination</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            In a <m>K</m>‑vector space <m>V</m>, a vector <m>v</m> is a linear combination of
            <m>u_1,\dots,u_n</m> if <m>v=a_1u_1+\cdots+a_nu_n</m> for some scalars <m>a_i\in K</m>. [1](https://mnscu-my.sharepoint.com/personal/jp9927jt_minnstate_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/BuskeVectorSpaceChapter.pdf)
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <definition xml:id="def-span">
        <title>Span</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For a subset <m>S\subseteq V</m>, the <em>span</em> of <m>S</m> is
            <m>\mathrm{span}(S)=\{a_1u_1+\cdots+a_ku_k: u_i\in S,\ a_i\in K,\ k\ge 1\}</m>.
            Even when <m>S</m> is infinite, each individual vector in the span is a <em>finite</em>
            linear combination. [1](https://mnscu-my.sharepoint.com/personal/jp9927jt_minnstate_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/BuskeVectorSpaceChapter.pdf)
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <definition xml:id="def-linear-independence">
        <title>Linear independence</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A finite set <m>\{u_1,\dots,u_k\}</m> is linearly independent if
            <m>a_1u_1+\cdots+a_ku_k=0</m> implies <m>a_1=\cdots=a_k=0</m>.  An infinite set
            <m>S</m> is linearly independent if every finite subset is linearly independent. 
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

        <example xml:id="ex-matrix-lc">
          <title>Matrix as a linear combination</title>
          <p>
            Express <m>\begin{bmatrix}1&3\\-1&2\end{bmatrix}</m> as a linear combination of
            <m>\begin{bmatrix}1&0\\0&1\end{bmatrix}</m>,
            <m>\begin{bmatrix}1&0\\0&-1\end{bmatrix}</m>,
            <m>\begin{bmatrix}0&1\\1&0\end{bmatrix}</m>,
            <m>\begin{bmatrix}0&-1\\1&0\end{bmatrix}</m>.  Solve the corresponding 4×4 system to find the coefficients. [1](https://mnscu-my.sharepoint.com/personal/jp9927jt_minnstate_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/BuskeVectorSpaceChapter.pdf)
          </p>
        </example>

        <example xml:id="ex-poly-lc">
          <title>Polynomial as a linear combination</title>
          <p>
            Write <m>p(x)=7x^2+4x-3</m> as a combination of <m>x^2,(x+1)^2,(x+2)^2</m> by matching coefficients. [1](https://mnscu-my.sharepoint.com/personal/jp9927jt_minnstate_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/BuskeVectorSpaceChapter.pdf)
          </p>
        </example>

        <example xml:id="ex-seq-span">
          <title>Span in a sequence space</title>
          <p>
            Let <m>e_k</m> be the sequence with a single 1 in position <m>k</m> and zeros elsewhere.
            The span of <m>\{e_0,e_1,e_2,\dots\}</m> equals the set of <em>finitely supported</em> sequences
            (all but finitely many zeros).  In particular, the all‑ones sequence is not in the span. [1](https://mnscu-my.sharepoint.com/personal/jp9927jt_minnstate_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/BuskeVectorSpaceChapter.pdf)
          </p>
        </example>

        <example xml:id="ex-sin-cos-indep">
          <title><m>\sin</m> and <m>\cos</m> are independent</title>
          <p>
            If <m>a\sin x+b\cos x=0</m> for all <m>x</m>, then evaluating at <m>0</m> and <m>\pi/2</m>
            forces <m>b=0</m> and <m>a=0</m>, so <m>\sin</m> and <m>\cos</m> are linearly independent in
            <m>\mathrm{Func}_{\mathbb{R},\mathbb{R}}</m>. 
        </example>
      </examples>

      <proposition xml:id="prop-redundant">
        <title>Redundancy in a dependent list</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>u_1,u_2,\dots</m> is a (finite or infinite) linearly dependent sequence, then some
            <m>u_j</m> is a linear combination of the earlier vectors <m>u_1,\dots,u_{j-1}</m>. 
          </p>
        </statement>
      </proposition>

      <proposition xml:id="prop-extend-indep">
        <title>Extending a linearly independent set</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>\{u_1,\dots,u_k\}</m> is linearly independent and <m>v\notin \mathrm{span}\{u_1,\dots,u_k\}</m>,
            then <m>\{u_1,\dots,u_k,v\}</m> is still linearly independent. [1](https://mnscu-my.sharepoint.com/personal/jp9927jt_minnstate_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/BuskeVectorSpaceChapter.pdf)
          </p>
        </statement>
      </proposition>

      <activities>
        <activity xml:id="act-span-matrix-poly">
          <title>Activity: Matching coefficients (two settings)</title>
          <p>
            (a) In <m>M_{2,2}</m>, determine coefficients to express
            <m>\begin{bmatrix}1&3\\0&0\end{bmatrix}</m> as a linear combination of
            <m>\begin{bmatrix}1&0\\0&1\end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix}0&1\\1&0\end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix}1&0\\1&1\end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix}0&1\\1&1\end{bmatrix}</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            (b) In <m>P_2</m>, decide if <m>p(x)=-x^2+x+2</m> lies in <m>\mathrm{span}\{x^2+x+1,\ 2x^2+x\}</m>.
            Explain via a solvable/unsolvable linear system. [1](https://mnscu-my.sharepoint.com/personal/jp9927jt_minnstate_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/BuskeVectorSpaceChapter.pdf)
          </p>
        </activity>

        <activity xml:id="act-indep-transform">
          <title>Activity: Independence under linear combinations</title>
          <p>
            Let <m>u,v,w</m> be linearly independent in <m>V</m>.  Analyze independence of
            <m>\{2u-w,\ w+v,\ 3v+\tfrac12 u\}</m> by reducing a dependence relation to one in
            <m>\{u,v,w\}</m>.  Justify each step clearly. [1](https://mnscu-my.sharepoint.com/personal/jp9927jt_minnstate_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/BuskeVectorSpaceChapter.pdf)
          </p>
        </activity>
      </activities>

