    <section xml:id="vs-subspaces">
      <title>Subspaces</title>

      <definition xml:id="def-subspace">
        <title>Subspace</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A subset <m>W\subseteq V</m> is a subspace if <m>0\in W</m>, <m>u,v\in W\Rightarrow u+v\in W</m>,
            and <m>k\in K, u\in W\Rightarrow ku\in W</m>. [1](https://mnscu-my.sharepoint.com/personal/jp9927jt_minnstate_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/BuskeVectorSpaceChapter.pdf)
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <examples>
        <example>
          <title>Continuous and differentiable functions</title>
          <p>
            The continuous (respectively, differentiable) real‑valued functions on <m>\mathbb{R}</m> form
            subspaces of <m>\mathrm{Func}_{\mathbb{R},\mathbb{R}}</m> by calculus closure laws. [1](https://mnscu-my.sharepoint.com/personal/jp9927jt_minnstate_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/BuskeVectorSpaceChapter.pdf)
          </p>
        </example>
        <example>
          <title>Linear recurrences</title>
          <p>
            The set of real sequences satisfying <m>a_{n+2}=a_{n+1}+a_n</m> is a subspace of
            <m>\mathrm{Seq}_{\mathbb{R}}</m> (closed under addition and scalar multiplication). [1](https://mnscu-my.sharepoint.com/personal/jp9927jt_minnstate_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/BuskeVectorSpaceChapter.pdf)
          </p>
        </example>
        <example>
          <title>Solution space of <m>f''=-f</m></title>
          <p>
            All solutions of <m>f''=-f</m> form a subspace of <m>\mathrm{Func}_{\mathbb{R},\mathbb{R}}</m>. [1](https://mnscu-my.sharepoint.com/personal/jp9927jt_minnstate_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/BuskeVectorSpaceChapter.pdf)
          </p>
        </example>
        <example>
          <title>Polynomials vanishing at a point</title>
          <p>
            <m>W=\{p\in P_2: p(r)=0\}</m> is a subspace of <m>P_2</m> for any fixed <m>r\in K</m>. [1](https://mnscu-my.sharepoint.com/personal/jp9927jt_minnstate_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/BuskeVectorSpaceChapter.pdf)
          </p>
        </example>
      </examples>

      <proposition xml:id="prop-span-smallest-subspace">
        <title>Span as smallest subspace</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For <m>S\subseteq V</m>, the span <m>\mathrm{span}(S)</m> is a subspace containing <m>S</m>,
            and it is contained in any other subspace containing <m>S</m>. [1](https://mnscu-my.sharepoint.com/personal/jp9927jt_minnstate_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/BuskeVectorSpaceChapter.pdf)
          </p>
        </statement>
      </proposition>

      <activity xml:id="act-equal-spans">
        <title>Activity: Comparing spans</title>
        <p>
          In <m>P_2</m>, show that <m>\{x^2-2x+1,\ x-1\}</m> and <m>\{x^2-1,\ x^2-x\}</m> span the same subspace
