    <section xml:id="vs-basis-dimension">
      <title>Basis and Dimension</title>

      <definition xml:id="def-basis">
        <title>Basis</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A set <m>B\subseteq V</m> is a <em>basis</em> if it is linearly independent and
            <m>\mathrm{span}(B)=V</m>. [1](https://mnscu-my.sharepoint.com/personal/jp9927jt_minnstate_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/BuskeVectorSpaceChapter.pdf)
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <definition xml:id="def-dimension">
        <title>Dimension</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>V</m> has a basis with <m>n</m> elements, then <m>\dim V=n</m>.  If every basis is infinite,
            then <m>\dim V=\infty</m>. [1](https://mnscu-my.sharepoint.com/personal/jp9927jt_minnstate_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/BuskeVectorSpaceChapter.pdf)
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <examples>
        <example>
          <title>Common dimensions</title>
          <p>
            <m>\dim \mathbb{R}^n=n</m>; <m>\dim P_2=3</m>; <m>\dim M_{m,n}=mn</m>; if <m>|X|=n</m> is finite then
            <m>\dim \mathrm{Func}_{X,K}=n</m>, but if <m>X</m> is infinite then the function space is infinite‑dimensional. [1](https://mnscu-my.sharepoint.com/personal/jp9927jt_minnstate_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/BuskeVectorSpaceChapter.pdf)
          </p>
        </example>

        <example>
          <title>An infinite basis for all polynomials</title>
          <p>
            In <m>P</m>, the set <m>\{1,x,x^2,\dots\}</m> is a basis; hence <m>\dim P=\infty</m>. [1](https://mnscu-my.sharepoint.com/personal/jp9927jt_minnstate_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/BuskeVectorSpaceChapter.pdf)
          </p>
        </example>

        <example>
          <title>Recurrence and differential equation spaces</title>
          <p>
            The space of sequences satisfying <m>a_{n+2}=a_{n+1}+a_n</m> has dimension 2; one basis is
            <m>\{(1,0,1,1,2,3,\dots),(0,1,1,2,3,5,\dots)\}</m>.  The solution space of <m>f''=-f</m> is
            two‑dimensional with basis <m>\{\sin x,\cos x\}</m>. [1](https://mnscu-my.sharepoint.com/personal/jp9927jt_minnstate_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/BuskeVectorSpaceChapter.pdf)
          </p>
        </example>
      </examples>

      <theorem xml:id="thm-existence-basis">
        <title>Every vector space has a basis</title>
        <statement>
          <p>Every vector space admits a basis (proof uses the axiom of choice in general).</p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>

      <theorem xml:id="thm-bases-same-size">
        <title>Bases have equal cardinality</title>
        <statement>
          <p>Any two bases of a vector space have the same size (finite or infinite).</p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>

      <proposition xml:id="prop-extend-shrink">
        <title>Extending and shrinking to bases</title>
        <statement>
          <ol>
            <li>Any linearly independent set can be extended to a basis of <m>V</m>.</li>
            <li>Any spanning set contains a basis (cast‑out redundant vectors).</li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
      </proposition>

      <activities>
        <activity xml:id="act-basis-castout">
          <title>Activity: Casting out to a basis</title>
          <p>
            In <m>P_2</m>, start from <m>S=\{1,\ x,\ 2x+1,\ x^2+1,\ x^2+2\}</m>.  Scan left‑to‑right, removing vectors
            that lie in the span of earlier ones, to produce a basis for <m>P_2</m>.  Explain each removal step. [1](https://mnscu-my.sharepoint.com/personal/jp9927jt_minnstate_edu/Documents/Microsoft%20Copilot%20Chat%20Files/BuskeVectorSpaceChapter.pdf)
          </p>
        </activity>

        <activity xml:id="act-basis-extend">
